            <h2> Keeping Up With Physical Health </h2>
            <p> <h6> 1.Physical activity is an important way to prevent heart disease – the nation’s No. 1 killer — and stroke, the nation’s No. 5 killer. </h6>
            <h6> 2.Do at least 2.5 hours of moderate intensity physical activity (think brisk walking), spread across the entire week, to improve your cardiovascular health. </h6>
            <h6> 3.People of all types, shapes, sizes and abilities can benefit from being physically active. </h6>
            <h6> 4. If you haven’t been active for a while, start at a comfortable pace. Gradually increase your exercise intensity and duration as your body adapts to regular activity.<br> Choose activities that are appropriate for you right now.</h6>
            <h6> 5. Added sugar provides empty calories and is believed to be a leading cause of diseases that kill millions of people each year. </h6>
            <h6> 6. The best diet for you is the one that works for you and you can stick to in the long term. </h6>
            <h6> 7. Vegetables are rich in all sorts of nutrients. Eating vegetables each day is associated with improved health and a lower risk of disease. </h6>
            <h6> 8. It is much more important to eat real, nutritious foods than to count on supplements to provide the nutrients you need. </h6>
            <h6> 9. Adopting a healthy lifestyle is the only way to ensure long-term weight loss and a lifetime of improved health. </h6>
            <h6> 10. During food processing, many of the beneficial nutrients in the food are removed, Also potentially harmful ingredients are added like added sugar and trans fats. </h6>
          </div>
