      <p> <h1> Maintaining Your Mental Health </h1> </p>

      <p> <text1> 1. Do your best to enjoy 15 minutes of sunshine, and apply sunscreen. Sunlight synthesizes Vitamin D, which experts believe is a mood elevator. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 2. Start your day with a cup of co­ffee or green tea. Consumption of both drinks is linked to lower rates of depression. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 3. Set up a getaway. The act of planning a vacation and having something to look forward to can boost your overall happiness for up to 8 weeks! </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 4. Work your strengths. Do something you're good at to build self-confidence, then tackle a tougher task. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 5. "You don’t have to see the whole staircase, just take the first step."  -Martin Luther King Jr. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 6. Show some love to someone in your life. Close, quality relationships are key for a happy, healthy life. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 7. Take time to laugh. Hang out with a funny friend, watch a comedy or check out cute videos online. Laughter helps reduce anxiety. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 8. Has something been bothering you? Let it all out…on paper. Writing about upsetting experiences can reduce symptoms of depression. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 9. Practice forgiveness - even if it's just forgiving that person who cut you off during your commute. People who forgive have better mental health and report being more satisfied with their lives. </text1>
      <br>
      <br>
      <text1> 10. Track gratitude and achievement with a journal.
        <br>
        (Like the one we have below!)
        <br>
        Include 3 things you are grateful for and 3 things you were able to accomplish each day. <text1> </p>
